context: <a0_0><b3_0>The framers of the US Constitution<b3_0/><a0_0/> were influenced by the Constitution of the Republic of the United Provinces, as <b4_0>Federalist No. 20<b4_0/>, by <a1_0>James Madison<a1_0/>, shows. Such influence appears, however, to have been of a <b7_0>negative<b7_0/> nature, as Madison describes the Dutch confederacy as exhibiting "Imbecility in the government; <b5_0>discord among the provinces<b5_0/>; foreign influence and indignities; a precarious existence in peace, and peculiar calamities from war." Apart from this, <b6_0>the American Declaration of Independence<b6_0/> is similar to <a2_0>the Act of Abjuration, essentially the declaration of independence of the United Provinces<a2_0/>, but concrete evidence that the former directly influenced the latter is absent.
